BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTART:20260314T180000Z
DTEND:20260314T200000Z
DTSTAMP:20260314T000000Z
SUMMARY:Women in the Struggle: Historic Stamps with Clarence McKnight (All ages welcome)
DESCRIPTION:\nFamilies are invited to learn about commemorative stamps 
 featuring women throughout history as presented by expert philatelist 
 Clarence McKnight. Learn about their contributions to the Civil Rights 
 movement\, and suffrage and equality\, and social justice. In addition to 
 examples from his collection\, Mr. McKnight will present a PowerPoint about 
 the stamps and the social justice champions who inspired them\, and will be 
 followed by guest speakers from the Montclair Chapter of NCNW (National 
 Council of Negro Women\, and young poets. \n\nDon’t miss this chance to 
 see Mr. McKnight’s singular collection up close! There will be 
 refreshments and snacks. Made possible by funds from the New Jersey State 
 Council on the Arts\, a partner agency of the National Endowment for the 
 Arts. Registration recommended for updates and reminders.\n\n“Come 
 Celebrate With Me” is a year-long series of programming honoring 100 
 years of observing Black history in America. Founded in 1926 by Carter G. 
 Woodson\, Negro History Week evolved into Black History Month\, opening the 
 door for additional annual commemorations such as Juneteenth\, Black Music 
 Month\, Caribbean Heritage Month\, Kwanzaa and more.\n\nMontclair Public 
 Library will honor the centennial of these commemorations in 2026 through a 
 series of programs designed to engage and connect participants while 
 highlighting and celebrating the experiences and contributions of people of 
 African descent in the United States.\n\n \n\nThis exhibit is from the 
 private collection of Clarence McKnight.\nI’ve been collecting stamps 
 since 1986. Over the years\, I have presented at churches in\nEssex and 
 Bergen County. I also presented to youth groups such as\, The Links\, 
 Jack\nand Jill in Montclair and Englewood\, New Jersey\, Scouting groups in 
 Montclair and\nelementary schools in Northern New Jersey\, New York and 
 most recently in Maryland\nand DC. Some of my presentations included Power 
 Point and videos presentations. I’ve\nalso setup exhibits and gave 
 presentations for Prudential Insurance in Hanover in New\nJersey\, Hoffman 
 Roche in Nutley\, New Jersey\, Municipality of East Orange 
 and\nMunicipality of Perth Amboy\, Perth Amboy Art Gallery\, Newark Museum. 
 Yogi Berra\nMuseum on Montclair University Campus\, New Jersey\, local 
 libraries (Montclair\,\nEdison\, Perth Amboy\, East Orange and Newark)\, 
 New York National Stamp show\,\nRutgers University in Newark\, Kean 
 University\, Passaic County Community College in\nWanaque and Passaic 
 campus\, Housing Authority of Passaic ( Senior Citizen Building)\nSpree 
 Village After School Program in Passaic\, plus Post Offices in Hudson\, 
 Bergen\,\nEssex and Passaic Counties\, Somerset Patriots Minor league 
 baseball team for Negro\nBaseball night. Throughout the years my exhibits 
 are during African American History\nMonth\, Hispanic Heritage Month\, 
 Women’s History Month and Negro League Baseball.\nI’m the former New 
 Jersey State Director\, editor of Reflections newsletter and board\nmember 
 of The Ebony Society of Philatelic Events and Reflections (ESPER)\, 
 an\ninternational stamp club promoting the collecting of African-Americans 
 on stamps. I’m\nthe webmaster for the award-winning ESPER website. For 
 more information visit:\nESPERSTAMPS.ORG Contact information: 
 clarencmac@aol.com
